I mentioned that I didn't think these volunteer lawyers were earning their keep in terms of the cost to send them.

1120
01:52:12,000 --> 01:52:17,000
But one thing which is undeniable is after being here for two or three or four weeks,

1121
01:52:17,000 --> 01:52:20,000
they go back home and it would change their lives.

1122
01:52:20,000 --> 01:52:29,000
And I, to this day, I'm hearing stories about lawyers who spent a short period of time either here or in Jackson or in Alabama.

1123
01:52:29,000 --> 01:52:36,000
And they are the head of the Human Rights Commission in Pittsburgh or Cincinnati or something of that sort.

1124
01:52:36,000 --> 01:52:42,000
And it really was like a contagion.

1125
01:52:42,000 --> 01:52:44,000
I got a very big dose.

1126
01:52:44,000 --> 01:52:48,000
But even for those smaller doses it was like a contagion and it's remarkable.

1127
01:52:48,000 --> 01:52:52,000
And this is true of the law students as well who would come down.

1128
01:52:52,000 --> 01:52:55,000
There was a group called law students civil committee for civil rights.

1129
01:52:55,000 --> 01:52:57,000
It was a listric.

1130
01:52:57,000 --> 01:53:05,000
And the law students were also changed and went into public service work or pro bono work.

1131
01:53:05,000 --> 01:53:09,000
So I just wanted to mention that because what you said.

1132
01:53:09,000 --> 01:53:18,000
I had been through all these experiences and not just legal but social.

1133
01:53:18,000 --> 01:53:23,000
And we haven't mentioned the Vietnam War but that was coming.

1134
01:53:23,000 --> 01:53:33,000
That was going on and I was meeting and spending time with anti-war activists and felt strongly about that too.

1135
01:53:33,000 --> 01:53:44,000
And I got to the point that I could just see that there was what I was interested in.

1136
01:53:44,000 --> 01:53:54,000
And I couldn't just see going back to a firm and being slaughtered into some anti-trust case representing one big corporation against another.

1137
01:53:54,000 --> 01:54:07,000
It just, by the time the two years was over I just knew I was going to do work in this area.

1138
01:54:07,000 --> 01:54:12,000
Not some other, you know, not a commercial area.

1139
01:54:12,000 --> 01:54:17,000
And I was very lucky to be able to do that actually.

1140
01:54:17,000 --> 01:54:21,000
Not only do it but do it on my own terms and my own law firm.

1141
01:54:21,000 --> 01:54:28,000
And the reason were these two union lawyers I mentioned to you before made it possible because they really got me into having a billing client.

1142
01:54:28,000 --> 01:54:30,000
All this stuff I've ever done in Louisiana.

1143
01:54:30,000 --> 01:54:38,000
And there's never, no one's ever paid anything for it except if you win a title seven case the court makes the defendant pay you which is nice.

1144
01:54:38,000 --> 01:54:43,000
But in terms of sustaining a law practice that's not a very good way to go about it.

1145
01:54:43,000 --> 01:54:50,000
So I felt I wanted to do that and I feel I was very lucky to be able to do that.

1146
01:54:50,000 --> 01:54:54,000
I don't know what else to say about it. It's just your mind is different.

1147
01:54:54,000 --> 01:55:06,000
When I left Donald and Porter I wanted that leave of absence. I wanted that security that I could come back and I wasn't going to be floating out there without a job.

1148
01:55:06,000 --> 01:55:11,000
And then by the first year was up I was kind of not so concerned about it although they extended it.

1149
01:55:11,000 --> 01:55:14,000
At the end of the second year it was just completely out of the question.

1150
01:55:14,000 --> 01:55:16,000
I had argued in the Supreme Court.

1151
01:55:16,000 --> 01:55:18,000
These are these young lawyers.

1152
